Do‚Äôs and Don‚Äôts for different users (students, researchers, staff)

üß™ 3. Hands-On Exercises
‚úçÔ∏è Exercise Set A: Grant Writing Prompts
Activity	Description	Tool
A1: Grant Discovery	Use a prompt to find 3 relevant grants for a health-AI collaboration.	ChatGPT + Dimensions.ai
A2: Proposal Drafting	Use RCR format to generate a 500-word draft proposal.	Claude
A3: Executive Summary	Write a 200-word summary using an ICE-based prompt.	ChatGPT
Supplement:
Provide grant template samples from Grantable.ai or existing proposals. Include sections like Problem, Method, Impact, Budget, Industry Role.

üìö Exercise Set B: Research-Based Prompts
üë©‚Äçüéì For Students:
Level	Task	Tool
Beginner	Summarize research method in 3 lines	ChatGPT
Intermediate	Write a mini lit review from 3 sources	Claude
Advanced	Identify gap + propose research plan	Claude or GPT-4
üë©‚Äçüè´ For Academic Staff:
Level	Task	Tool
Beginner	Draft email to initiate collaboration	ChatGPT
Intermediate	Generate abstract for joint paper	Claude
Advanced	Create research roadmap with KPIs	Claude or Notion AI
Supplement:
Provide evaluation rubrics to compare prompt effectiveness by output structure, relevance, and clarity.

üõ† Exercise Set C: Industry Use Case Prompts
Category	Prompt Activity	Tool
Manufacturing	Suggest 3 AI tools for automation	ChatGPT
Sustainability	Write a 1-page carbon footprint proposal	Claude
Smart Cities	Map potential partners for urban AI project	ChatGPT + Dimensions.ai
Supplement:
Provide use case brief templates, and include industry background scenarios for role-play.



Grant making in a process: 
Have a look at these prompt: 
Prompt 1: Project Introduction
I'm preparing a grant application for a community health initiative focused on reducing diabetes in underserved urban neighborhoods through nutrition education and free screening programs. We're targeting the [Foundation Name] Community Health Grant for $75,000 over 18 months. Please help me develop a strong application.
Content Quality Testing Prompts
Prompt 2: Executive Summary
Based on our community health initiative, please write a compelling 250-word executive summary that highlights the need, our approach, expected outcomes, and why our organization is qualified to implement this program.
Prompt 3: Problem Statement
Help me develop a data-driven problem statement about diabetes prevalence in urban communities, emphasizing health disparities and social determinants. Include 3-4 relevant statistics that make a compelling case for our intervention.
Technical Writing Testing Prompts
Prompt 4: Language Refinement
Please review and improve this draft paragraph for clarity, conciseness, and grant-appropriate terminology: "Our program will do diabetes screenings and teach people about eating better in the community. We will work with local partners to reach more people and make sure the program continues even after the grant money is gone. We think we can help about 500 people in the first year."
Prompt 5: Technical to Accessible Translation
Transform this technical description into accessible language while maintaining acc

Structure Testing Prompts
Prompt 6: Outline Development
Create a detailed outline for our complete grant proposal following standard foundation grant structure. Include all major sections with brief descriptions of what should be included in each.
Prompt 7: Timeline Creation
Develop a 18-month timeline for our diabetes prevention program that shows key implementation phases, milestones, and evaluation points in a logical sequence.
Customization Testing Prompts
Prompt 8: Funder Alignment
The [Foundation Name] priorities include "sustainable community solutions," "health equity," and "innovative approaches." Revise our project description to specifically highlight how our diabetes prevention program aligns with these three priority areas.
Prompt 9: Community Context
Our target community is a predominantly Hispanic and African American neighborhood with high poverty rates (32%), limited healthcare access (40% uninsured), and food desert conditions. Enhance our needs assessment with specific language addressing these contextual factors.
Strategic Value Testing Prompts
Prompt 10: Outcomes and Impact Framework
Develop SMART objectives and corresponding outcome measures for our diabetes prevention program, including short-term, intermediate, and long-term impacts. Include both quantitative and qualitative measurement approaches.
Prompt 11: Sustainability Planning
Create a comprehensive sustainability paragraph explaining how our diabetes prevention program will continue after grant funding ends. Include potential funding sources, community partnerships, and resource leveraging strategies.
Iterative Improvement Testing Prompts
Prompt 12: Feedback Integration
A preliminary reviewer noted our proposal "lacks specific information about community involvement in program design and implementation." Please revise our methodology section to address this feedback, emphasizing community engagement throughout the project lifecycle.
Prompt 13: Budget Narrative Refinement
Review this budget narrative and strengthen the justification for our staffing costs, which the review committee flagged as potentially high: "The project requires a full-time Program Coordinator ($52,000) and part-time Health Educator ($25,000) to implement all activities. Administrative support will be provided in-kind by our organization."
Final Assessment Prompt
Prompt 14: Comprehensive Review
Please review our complete grant proposal (I'll paste sections below) and identify the three strongest elements and three areas that most need improvement before submission. [Paste consolidated proposal sections from previous responses]
 

üìÑ 4. Pre- and Post-Workshop Assessments
‚úÖ Pre-Workshop (Before)
How confident are you in using AI for collaboration tasks?

Have you used tools like ChatGPT/Claude before?

Rate your familiarity with grant writing or research summaries.

‚úÖ Post-Workshop (After)
What AI tool do you feel most comfortable using?

Can you now draft a grant summary or research abstract with AI?

What was your biggest takeaway from the hands-on prompts?

Format: Google Form / Typeform / Paper Handout


